{For any tournament player, to play Larsen is an important goal. For a club
player as myself (only six tourneys, all in Galicia region) it is simply a
wonderful gift. The history of this game began when our top board Ferreiro
vacated from justified family reasons. And so I played.} 1. e4 e5 {Throughout
he game, or at least most of it, the pure fact I could play Larsen was a
magnificent lesson for me. I did not even dream about winning or even drawing
the game. Against Caro-Kann I planned to sacrifice on e6 as Tal vs Botvinnik;
against Sicilian I thought about Morra Gambit. But now I had to find new lines.
} 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Bc4 Nf6 5. O-O {Here 5. e5 could objectively be
stronger, but I wanted to know how I could play this line. I though about 5.
Ng5 as well. Too bad I cannot play Larsen every day.} Nxe4 6. Re1 d5 7. Bxd5
Qxd5 8. Nc3 Qa5 9. Nxe4 Be6 10. Bd2 {I ran out of book on previous move. After
the game I was told that the normal move here is Neg5.} Qf5 {Already after the
game I found in the book by Maximo Borrell, that Black's position in this book
is superior.} 11. Bg5 {However, I liked my position.} f6 ({after} 11... Bb4 {
I thought to respond} 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4) (11... Bc5 {loses the piece after
} 12. Nh4 Qd5 13. c4 dxc3 (13... Qxc4 14. Rc1) 14. Qxd5 Bxd5 15. Nxc5+) ({while
} 11... h6 {is met with} 12. Bh4 g5 13. Nxd4) 12. Nh4 Qd5 13. Bxf6 Kd7 {
Threatening Re8, so White has to play actively.} 14. c4 Qxc4 15. Rc1 {After
the game it was discussed, that the opponent underestimated this move. I think,
however, that Larsen realized that after 15. .. Qd5 White's attacking chances
would finally lead to the inevitable strike Rc5.} Qxa2 16. Bxg7 Bxg7 17. Nc5+
Kc8 18. Nxe6 Bh6 {Larsen thought 15 minutes before making this move - almost
doubling his time consumption. Possibly it is the best move.} 19. Qg4 Kb8 {Of
course if Bxc1 then mate in 5 follows.} 20. Qg3 Qa5 21. b4 Qb6 22. Nc5 Rd8 23.
Re8 Rxe8 (23... Bxc1 24. Nd7+ Kc8 25. Qh3 {should force victory}) 24. Nd7+ Kc8
25. Qh3 {An important move which prevents safe shelter after Kb8.} Kd8 {Forced.
} 26. Nxb6 axb6 27. Rd1 Ra2 28. Nf3 {Avoiding Rd2 which would save pawn d4.}
Bf8 29. b5 Ne5 30. Nxd4 Bd6 31. Ne6+ Ke7 32. Ng7 {It has to be mentioned, that
after move 27 I asked Dr. Jesus Lopez, captain of my team, if I could offer
draw. He asked me what I would have done if he was Black, and I answered that
I would win easily. So he ordered me to continue. The final comment could be
simply: Thank You, Sr. Larsen!} (32. Ng7 Rea8 33. Qe6+ Kf8 34. Qf6+ Nf7 35.
Ne6+ Ke8 36. Re1 Be5 37. Ng5) 1-0

